title: Finding periodicity in everyday life using long-term observation of Bluetooth discovery
title_en: Finding periodicity in everyday life using long-term observation of Bluetooth discovery
abstract: 本研究は長期的な短距離無線探索ログを用いて日常生活における出現パターンの周期性を検出することを目的としている。研究では本研究の実装として定期的な探索を長期間運用し、デバイス識別子（BDA）を収集して複数日の午前・午後のセッションで得られた検出結果（1回の探索で概ね10–100台の検出）を用いて周期性と識別性およびプライバシー影響を解析した。
abstract_en: This study aims to detect periodicity in everyday presence patterns using long-term short-range wireless discovery logs. The study implemented continuous periodic discovery to collect device identifiers (BDA) and analyzed detection results obtained across multiple days and morning/afternoon sessions (approximately 10–100 devices detected per discovery) to evaluate periodicity, identifiability, and privacy impacts.
positioning_summary: 本研究は都市環境における遍在的センサインフラと短距離無線によるセンシングの文脈で、日常の社会的文脈検出に短距離無線探索ログが有用であると位置づけている。本研究は都市居住者や行動・生態モニタリングを行う研究領域に対して短距離無線探索ログを用いた周期性検出が直接関連すると説明している。
positioning_summary_en: This study positions itself within urban pervasive sensor infrastructure and short-range wireless sensing, arguing that short-range wireless discovery logs are useful for detecting social context in everyday life. This study explains that the use of discovery logs for periodicity detection is directly relevant to researchers and applications focused on urban residents and behavioral or ecological monitoring.
purpose_summary: 本研究の目的は長期の短距離無線探索観測から人や物の出現パターンに潜む周期性を明らかにすることである。目的として本研究はデバイス識別子（BDA）を識別子として扱うことの有用性とそのプライバシーに関する影響のギャップを明示的に検討している。
purpose_summary_en: The purpose of this study is to reveal periodicity hidden in appearance patterns of people and objects from long-term short-range wireless discovery observations. The purpose of this study includes explicitly examining the usefulness of device identifiers (BDA) as identifiers and the resulting gap concerning privacy impacts.
method_summary: 本研究は定期的な探索スキャンを長期運用して各スキャンで検出されるデバイス識別子（BDA）を収集する実装を行った。方法として本研究は2009年6月に複数日の午前と午後の時間帯で繰り返しスキャンを実施し、各スキャンで概ね10–100台のデバイス検出データを構築して周期性検出を試みた。
method_summary_en: This study implemented long-term periodic discovery scans to collect device identifiers (BDA) detected in each scan. The method in this study conducted repeated scans across multiple days in June 2009 during morning and afternoon time slots and constructed datasets with approximately 10–100 device detections per scan to attempt periodicity detection.
evaluation_summary: 本研究は2009年6月の複数日実験で午前と午後に分けて定期的な探索を実行するという実験手法で評価を行った。評価結果として本研究は1回の探索で概ね10–100台のデバイス検出を記録し、検出された出現パターンから周期性を解析すると同時にデバイス識別子の識別性とプライバシー影響を評価した。
evaluation_summary_en: This study evaluated its approach by running periodic discovery experiments across multiple days in June 2009 with separate morning and afternoon sessions. The evaluation in this study observed approximately 10–100 device detections per discovery, analyzed appearance patterns to extract periodicity, and assessed the identifiability of device identifiers (BDA) as well as associated privacy impacts.

Authors: Tatsuya Ushikoshi, Yasuyuki Kono, Satoshi Nakamura

The study implemented continuous periodic discovery to collect device identifiers (BDA) and analyzed detection results obtained across multiple days and morning/afternoon sessions (approximately 10–100 devices detected per discovery) to evaluate periodicity, identifiability, and privacy impacts.

This study explains that the use of discovery logs for periodicity detection is directly relevant to researchers and applications focused on urban residents and behavioral or ecological monitoring.
Purpose Summary: The purpose of this study is to reveal periodicity hidden in appearance patterns of people and objects from long-term short-range wireless discovery observations. The purpose of this study includes explicitly examining the usefulness of device identifiers (BDA) as identifiers and the resulting gap concerning privacy impacts.
Method Summary: This study implemented long-term periodic discovery scans to collect device identifiers (BDA) detected in each scan. The method in this study conducted repeated scans across multiple days in June 2009 during morning and afternoon time slots and constructed datasets with approximately 10–100 device detections per scan to attempt periodicity detection.
Evaluation Summary: This study evaluated its approach by running periodic discovery experiments across multiple days in June 2009 with separate morning and afternoon sessions. The evaluation in this study observed approximately 10–100 device detections per discovery, analyzed appearance patterns to extract periodicity, and assessed the identifiability of device identifiers (BDA) as well as associated privacy impacts.
